Title: Westralia gift book :
Summary: Various artists and writers from that state produced stories, verses, drawings and articles, at no cost, for the publication. Co-edited by Walter Murdoch, W. Siebenhaar, Alfred Carson and Alfred Chandler. The foreword is written by Walter Murdoch, Professor of English at the University of Western Australia. Lieutenant Hugo Throssell VC, who had been invalided home, was asked to contribute an article to the Gift Book outlining his time with the 10th Light Horse Regiment on Gallipoli in 1915 and especially the incident on 29 August 1915 for which he was awarded the Victoria Cross. This provides one of the most detailed personal accounts from an Australian VC recipient at Gallipoli of the events surrounding the achievement of the award.

Creator: Turner, James Leslie,
Title: James Leslie Turner World War I postcards collection.
Summary: James Leslie Turner, a lance sergeant of the 28th Battalion from Fremantle has been sending photographic postcards, some in colour, of  England and France to members of his family in Western Australia whilst serving with the Australian forces in World War I. The postcards were sent from various camps in Alexandria, Marseilles, London, Wool, Wareham in Dorset, Andover on Salisbury Plain, Fovant in Wiltshire, Le Havre in Haute-Normandie and Reims in France's Champagne-Ardenne region. He died of wounds on 11 June 1918 in France. The collection includes three postcards from his acquaintance, William Omond of New South Wales, who was also serving the Australian Imperial Force (A. I. F.).

Title: 11th Battalion A.I.F. on the steps of the Great Pyramid of Cheops in Egypt, 10 January 1915
Notes: Group portrait of all the original officers and men of the 11th Battalion, 3rd Brigade AIF on the Great Pyramid of Cheops. Officers identified in the first row are, left to right: 2nd Lt F P Strickland; 2nd Lt J Newman; Maj S R Roberts; Lt J H Morgan; Capt J S Denton; Capt A E J Croly; Capt Charles A Barnes; Lt K McLennan; Padre Fahey; Lt (later Capt) A P H Corley (KIA 17 Sept. 1915); Lt (Later Capt) C A La Nauze (KIA 28 June 1915); Capt J H  Peck; Capt W R Annear; Capt R R Reilly; 2nd Lt M L Reid; Lt D H MacDonald; Lt Col J L Johnston; Capt R W Everett; Maj E A Drake-Brockman; Capt E T Brennan; Capt R L Leane; 2nd Lt A H Darnell; 2nd Lt A H Priestley; Lt W H Rockliff; 2nd Lt J H Cooke (KIA 10 Apr. 1916); 2nd Lt H James; 2nd Lt C F Buttle; 2nd Lt H H Walker (sitting); Lt J Williams (top). Photograph is dated from Capt Barnes' diary which records the event [information from Australian War Memorial catalogue];The man at centre top of the pyramid has been identified as David Simcock (known as Pink Top) died at Gallipoli 2 May 1915.;Sitting to the right of David Simcock is Private William Murray. (Information supplied by family member who notes that somewhere in this photograph is another family member Pte Charles Herbert Jones 2816 KIA in France 3 July 1916);Charles Canning Gallaher (left) and  Douglas Wallace Gallaher (right), each with right hand raised are in the centre at the feet of the drummer near the top of the group of men. (Identified by a copy held by family marked by Douglas Gallaher: 'Eleventh Battalion WA at the base of a pyramid  Douglas wrote on the photograph. "Taken before we left for the front, can see me marked with a cross and Charles along side, very few of the Batt left now." He was wounded at Gallipoli 4 May 1915 and killed in France 3 June 1916. Charles was wounded at Gallipoli and repatriated home - the only one of four Gallaher brothers to return);Information on the back of the image owned by the Battye Library indicates that this is a photograph of the 28th Battalion, however it has been proved to be a photograph of the 11th Battalion AIF.;This image was received in two collections.

Title: Snapshots from a Western Australian in the First World War.
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.;The captions are very difficult to read with both T and G often looking like S.
Summary: This album contains photographs relating to WWI in Western Australia, Gallipoli and Egypt. First names have been used in captions so that the men have not been identified. One man named as Capt Brennan may be Captain Denis Aloyisius Brennan of the 28th Battalion. Scattered throughout the album are snapshots labelled Anatarta Bay and Gaba Tepe and dated 25-26 April 1915, these relate to Gallipoli. There are also photographs of: presentation of colours to the 10th Light Horse, 1915, 10th Light Horse at Rockingham, 1915; 9th Reinforcement of the 10th Light Horse; bivouac of the 11th Battalion in Egypt; 11th Battalion on parade; 28th Battalion march in St George's Terrace; officers of the 28th Battalion; 4th Field Ambulance; Blackboy Hill; the Ajana troopship leaving Sydney 18 December 1914; Engineers leaving on the Katoomba 2 October 1915.
Captions for URLs: 4083B: Album of snapshots from a Western Australian in WWI, 1914-1915

Title: The Egyptian Times and The Australian published on 25 April 1919.
Notes: Title supplied by cataloguer.;Digitised as part of the World War I Centenary Project.;This broadsheet is likely to be a newspaper supplement published as a wrap with Daily News or The West Australian on 25 April 1919 (Anzac Day) in an effort to raise money for R.S.A. and it advertises an interesting programme for "A Night in Cairo", a fund-raising event held at Esplanade Gardens, St George's Terrace at 7.30 p.m. that evening.
Summary: A newspaper broadsheet with The Egyptian Times flag on the front page (recto) and page 2 and The Australian on page 3 and 4 of the verso. Published on 25 April, 1919. Verso is headed The Australian 25 April 1919. Both sides contain Western Australian advertisements, articles and poems about the Gallipoli and R.S.A., such as, The Glory of Gallipoli: the fight that cannot fade and In the R.S.A. by Coo-ee.

Summary: Formerly PR2946.;A programme booklet featuring the Anzac Day Sports held at Australian Base Depots in Rouelles, France on April 25th 1919 under the distinguished patronage of Brigadier General Burrowes, Commandant British Base, Le Havre, Le Contre-Amiral Didelot, Governor of Havre and other officials. Creator: Maley, Westley Bellingham,
Title: Westley Bellingham Maley war memoirs.
Description: 1 volume (2 unnumbered leaves, 42 leaves, 13 leaves, 3 unnumbered leaves, 2 leaves, 13 unnumbered leaves), 2 x-rays, 1 postcard.
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Typescript memoir, written by Westley Bellingham Maley. He relates his experiences during his World War I service. "To my dear nephew James Addison Harwood from Uncle West" is written in pen on the first page. The memoir is written in two parts, part one: "Black Boy Hill to Dickiebusch" and part two: "Guns on the Western Front". The x-rays show  a piece of shrapnel which pierced the diaphragm and lodged in Maley's chest. The postcard is of the hospital ship "Wandilla". Maley has written in pencil on it, describing his trip from Bristol to Alexandria, where he was transferred to the General Hospital. From there he continued from Suez to Fremantle on the Australian hospital ship Koroola.
Captions for URLs: Black Boy Hill to Dickiebusch and Guns on the Western Front

Creator: Simmons, George Alfred,
Title: Interview with George Simmons /
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: George Simmons was born in 1894. This interview discussed his early life and family circumstances in England prior to World War I. Geroge Simmons was enlisted in 1914 to the Royal Naval Air Service as a seaman and was promoted to Flight Sergeant. Attached to the 211 Squadron - Royal Flying Corps from 1914 to 1918, he saw action over France as an air gunner and air crew observer. He discussed living in England during the Great Depression and before World War II, the bombing of London and the conditions after World War II. He migrated to Australia in 1979.
Captions for URLs: OH4010 Part 1: Interview with George Simmons in 1982;OH4010 Part 2: Interview with George Simmons in 1982;OH4010 Transcript: Interview with George Simmons in 1982

Creator: Caporn, Douglas Roy,
Title: Interview with Douglas Roy Caporn /
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Douglas Roy (Rocca) Caporn was born in 1896. In this interview, he discussed his family life growing up in Claremont. In 1914, he joined the Citizen Military Services Infantry - 16th Battalion based in Fremantle and Rottnest Island. Enlisted in 1914 in the Western Australian 10th Light Horse Regiment, serving in Egypt, Suez, and Gallipoli (at "the Net", Walkers Ridge, Canterbury Slopes). He discussed his impressions of the war and Gallipoli such as life in the trenches, the Turkish soldiers, treatment of the horses, Battle of Romani and Suez Canal.
Captions for URLs: Interview with Douglas Roy Caporn / by Bill Edgar. ;Transcript. Interview with Douglas Roy Caporn / by Bill Edgar

Title: The 51st Battalion Memorial Cross erected on the battlefield of Villers-Bretonneux in 1918.
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: The inscription reads: R.I.P. to the memory of officers. N.C.O.'s & Men of the 51st Battn A.I.F. who fell in the counter attack on Villers Brettonnaux (sic) 24/25/4/18.;The cross had been erected on the battlefield by Sergeant Joe Tunnecliffe of Yanchep. Shells were roaring overhead as a memorial service was conducted by the chaplain of the 13th Brigade Padre Donald Blackwood. The cross was returned by the memorial authorities to Australia after World War One and was handed over to the 51st Militia Battalion at Ryde New South Wales. Because the 51st Battalion was largely a West Australian Unit, The State Executive of the RSL sought a transfer of the cross to St George`s Cathedral in Perth. In 1949, the parishioners at Ryde voted against a transfer. n 1956, by mutual agreement between the parishioners of the church and the 51st Battalion AIF Association, the cross was transferred to St George`s Cathedral in Perth. (Information from http://monumentaustralia.org.au/themes/conflict/ww1/display/60963-51st-battalion-memorial-cross)
Subject: Topical: 51st Battalion Memorial Cross;War memorials;World War, 1914-1918;Online image.

Title: Maurice Hamilton Joseph Otto in uniform.
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer, identified from captions under other photographs in the album. Caption in album: 1919.
Summary: Maurice Hamilton Joseph Otto known in the family as Joseph. Son of Johan Henry and Marie Lucie Zelie Otto De Grancy. However, Maurice's birth is registered (in Albany) with the family name Otto and Maurice appears to have continued using that name all his life including on his enlistment papers and at his burial in Karrakatta Cemetery. Other members of the family were at various times using the family name Otto De Grancy or De Grancy.
Captions for URLs: BA292/1/24: Maurice Hamilton Joseph Otto in uniform, 1919

Creator: White, Gordon,
Title: Interview with Gordon White /
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Gordon White was born in 1896. In this interview, he described his family life growing up in Perth and then land clearing and farming around the Morawa area. In 1916, he was enlisted and stationed at Blackboy Hill Camp before joining the Western Australian 10th Light Horse Regiment, serving in Egypt, Syria and Palestine.  He took part in the Battle of Romani; the capture of Damascus, the Battle of Beersheba; and Gaza campaigns. He was part of the peace-keeping forces in Egypt until 1919. He discussed his impressions of war, the different campaigns, the different armies in the conflicts and the military equipment.
Captions for URLs: OH4012 Part 1: Interview with Gordon White in 1983;OH4012 Part 2: Interview with Gordon White in 1983;OH4012 Transcript: Interview with Gordon White in 1983

Creator: Returned & Services League of Australia.
Title: Returned & Services League of Australia WA Branch Incorporated records
Summary: Includes records relating to the WA Branch, sub-branches, war veterans homes and retirement homes, State and National Congresses. Some national RSL records that relate to Western Australia are included. Records include appeals, circulars, constitutions, correspondence, events and functions, financial records, membership details, minutes, reports, rules and by-laws.

Creator: Roscoe, William Fenwick,
Title: Scrapbook of items concerning the 3rd Field Ambulance and some other Australian soldiers.
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.;The scrapbook is now known to have been created by W.F. Roscoe who was the bugler of the 3rd Field Ambulance. (Family members recognize his handwriting in the captions and he appears in some of the photographs. July 2015). The scrapbook was donated anonymously.
Summary: The scrapbook includes photographs, a leave and railway ticket, a betting slip from the Alexandria Sporting Club, and some newspaper cuttings. Photographs of: groups belonging to the 3rd Field Ambulance; dressing station at Gallipoli (4343B/7/36), the beach at Gallipoli (4343B/7/40): Algernon Fittall Pilcher and Ernie Pilcher at Gallipoli (4343B/7/38); Egypt; George Ford in France August 1916 (4343B/7/26); Frank Christie and Bill Chamberlin in Egypt (4343B/7/39); newspaper cuttings of portraits of soldiers of the 3rd Field Ambulance and some other W.A. battalions. 4343B/7/42 is a photograph of part of C Section of 3rd Field Ambulance at Blackboy Hill. Includes John Simpson [Kirkpatrick] 3rd from left (with hand on hat). On the back cover a clipping featuring the Nukarnie Cricket Team which includes W.F. Roscoe.

Creator: Fitzmaurice, Jim,
Title: Interviews with Jim Fitzmaurice and Sir Norman Brearley in 1976 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (1 hr., 2 min., 13 sec.) :;1 online resource (2 MS Word files (16 and 14 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Side 1- Jim Fitzmaurice talks about his reasons for immigrating from Liverpool, England to Western Australia in 1910 at age 20; and living in Katanning before enlisting at the beginning of World War 1. One of the original members of the 10th Light Horse Regiment he speaks about his involvement at Gallipoli and of having to buy his own horse to take with him. He speaks about the Battle of the Wazza that took place in Cairo between the soldiers and police; events in Palestine (November 1918) assisting injured troops; importance of caring for his horse;  conscription; and finally returning home and establishing a business.;Side 2- Sir Norman Brearley talks of his recollections of the beginning of WW1, finishing his engineering apprenticeship before enlisting and then in 1915 worked his passage to England on the ship Western Australia to join the Royal Flying Corps. He speaks about:- Gallipoli; being shot down over France in November 1916; Bambra ship; 3rd Battalion King's Liverpool Regiment; Ypres (Ieper); food parcels; conscription; flying school/skills;  Australian Flying Corps; phosporous bombs; and the enlisted men from other countries (American, Canadian, Belgium). Promoted in 1918 to Major in the Royal Flying Corps and became instructor in one of the first flying schools near Rugby.
Subject: Topical: World War, 1914-1918;World War, 1914-1918;World War, 1914-1918;World War, 1914-1918;World War, 1914-1918;Aeronautics, Military;Aeronautics

Creator: Baron-Hay, G. K.
Title: Interview with George Baron-Hay in 1976 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (32 min., 46 sec.) :;1 online resource (2 MS Word files (16 and 14 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: George Kingston Baron-Hay, enlisted in the Australian Imperial Force on 26 June 1916, served on the Western Front of the 51st Battalion from June 1917 as the second lieutenant. George talks about his recollections of World War One (WWI), Gallipoli, 4 August 1918, enemy attack at Hourges, France, Battle of Somme and the formation and esprit de corps of the 51st Battalion; trench warfare - conditions in the trenches and battle strategies; command structures; different fighting styles of the men (American, French, Italian); prisoners of war; Mills bombs. George Kingston Baron-Hay joined the Department of Agriculture in 1922 as and agricultural advisor and was later made the director of Agriculture. He was awarded the Military Cross in 1918 and received the Commander of the British Empire (CBE) honour in 1961.

Creator: Ashton, Frederick,
Title: Interview with Fred Ashton and John McCleery in 1976 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (49 min., 15 sec.) :;1 online resource (2 MS Word files (13 pages, 11 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Side 1 - Fred Ashton speaks of enlisting in the 11th Battalion and receiving basic training at the Blackboy Hill camp. He speaks in detail of the Gallipoli landing and being captured by the Turks. Prisoner of war (POW) for over three years, he speaks of his feelings about his captors and the treatment he received as a POW. ;Side 2 - John McCleery speaks of his life before World War One (WWI) and the lack of understanding of what the war would be like. Explains about the months before the Gallipoli landing and becoming a platoon commander. Gives insight into the landing and what was happening around him;  about being wounded, evacuated ten days into the battle, his operation and convalescing in Fremantle.  Speaks of life after the war and of being one of the few that returned.

Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Side 1 - Mark Payne - Private in the 16th Battalion AIF enlisted as a mechanic but was put into the transport division, which contained only horse, before being transferred to the infantry. He talks about:- his time in France during the war and the loss of four years of his life including suffering from shell shock; difference in pay between the Australian and British troops; waiting 18 months to go home after the end of the war; the Somme, Poziares; Passchendaele; Villers-Bretonneux; Amiens; Etape; military police; shell shock and mustard gas; German prisoners of war (POW).;Side 2 - Alfred Thomas Lay enlisted in the 11th Battalion AIF after lying about his age. Alf speaks about the young men who enlisted at the same time and of the many battles fought before losing his leg on 10th August 1918. he speaks of - Blackboy Hill training Camp; Passchendaele; Villers-Bretonneux;  Kaisers Household Cavalry; Brigadier Gordon Bennet; General Monash; Hindenberg Line;  Baron Von Richthofen; and mateship - reminisces about his mates and the war.
Subject: Topical: World War, 1914-1918;Somme, 1st Battle of the, France, 1916.;World War, 1914-1918;World War, 1914-1918;World War, 1914-1918

Creator: Kahan, Henry Kagan,
Title: Interviews with Harry Kahan, Mr Booth, William James Purvis, and Stanley William Nixon in 1976 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (78 min., 16 sec.) :;1 online resource (2 MS Word files (16 pages, 12 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Side 1 - Kahan discusses his experiences fighting in the 28th Battalion during World War 1 (WW1). His descriptive recollections of events include discussion on mateship, military equipment (rifles, bayonet, revolvers , pistols rations, haversack); trench warfare and conditons in the trenches;  battles - Gallipoli, Pozieres, Passchendaele, Flers, the Somme; Bullecourt, France; 44th Battalion;  and the Turks.;Side 2 - i. Interview with Mr Booth about his recollections of both the Boer War and World War 1. He joined the British army at age 13  and mentions the Nottingham Derbyshire Regiment, Staffordshire and Leicester Regiment, and the Chesterfield Coldstream Guards.His wife and child were killed during the war and he immigrated to Australia in 1920. (Interview incomplete). William Purvis was a private with the 51st Battalion. He fought in France at the Somme and Pozieres and recalls the conditions in the trenches especially the mud. He sustained trench feet and never really recovered. Stanley Nixon enlisted in the 16th Battalion and talks of conscription, mateship, and trench conditions; Gallipoli and many of the battle in France -The Somme, Villers-Bretonneux, Ypres; the Hindenberg Lines, propoganda.

Title: Interview with Fred Boyd in 1979 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (58 min., 20 sec.) :;1 online resource (1 MS Word file (32 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Enlisted in the 28th Battalion in 1916 aged 17,  Frederick Samuel Joseph Boyd recounts his experiences during the war at the front in France. Talks of the battles on the Western Front -the Somme, Ypres, Salient, Mont St Quentin and being gassed and wounded several times; the military hospitals and the effect that being gassed had on the rest of his life; returning to Australia in 1919 and life after the war up to the Depression.

Creator: Bain, Evan,
Title: Interview with Evan Bain in 1979 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (59 min., 25 sec.) ;1 online resource (1 MS Word file (27 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Born in Inverness, Scotland, Evan talks about life in Katanning and joining the 10th Light Horse at age 20. Place of enlistment, Woodlands Station, Western Australia. He had four brothers in the war- one killed at Gallipoli, one wounded in France, he himself was wounded at the Front. Describes Gallipoli and the Battle of the Nek, trench warfare and conditions, Colonel Noel Brazier, Captain Vernon Piesse and the relief of leaving Gallipoli for spell on Lemnos Island and the final withdrawal. Talks about life after the war moving to the country helped get over the war and the total romance of it.

Creator: Whittington, Aubrey,
Title: Interview with Aubrey Whittington in 1979 /
Description: 1 audiocassette (1 hr., 3 sec.) :;1 online resource (1 MS Word file (27 pages)) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Seeing the war as an adventure and something different to do, he enlisted in the 16th Batallion (Infantry) in 1915. Talks about:-  landing at Gallipoli and the Commanders;  being Injured at Gallipoli, Simpson's Donkey, and being evacuated to the hospital ship and then England after seven days fighting; returning to the frontline - Battle of Somme; Hindenburg Line; failure of the tanks. Captured and prisoner of war (POW) for 19 months he talks about the hard conditions as POW and receipt of Red Cross parcels and the several escape attempts. Returned to Western Australia in 1919 he talks about the resettlement assistance offered by Repatriation Department.

Creator: Robertson, Evelyn Hay,
Title: Evelyn Hay Robertson papers.
Description: 1 autograph album (1 volume (164 unnumbered pages)) :;1 online resource (174 pages) :
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.;Digital preservation in TIFF format.
Summary: Autograph album thought to have been collected by Evelyn (?Witty?) Hay Robertson (born 1900) starting when she was about 16 years of age. It contains signatures from family and friends from 1916-1924 from various locations including Blackboy Camp, No. 9 Barrack Street, North Perth, Bunbury, Claremont, Cottesloe Beach and Subiaco. It has some illustrations by Harry Vernon Highman and entries from his father, Harry Vauneville Highman, which includes a poem, "Gallipoli 1915 The conflict". Witty Robertson married Harry Vernon Highman in 1925. Subsequently they divorced in 1957. Harry Vernon Highman married Doris Ruby Halligan in 1957 and after her death in 1966, Vernon Highman remarried Witty Robertson in 1968. After the death of Vernon in 1972, Witty married Francis Alexander Thomas in 1973. She passed away in 1999. The papers include marriage and death certificates, Harry's will and Harry's family history records. The collection also includes printouts from the Metropolitan Cemetries Board (MCB) of Witty and family members of Vernon Highman.

Creator: Greaves, Lilian Wooster,
Title: Lilian Wooster Greaves collection of World War I postcards.
Notes: Title devised by cataloguer.
Summary: Eight embroidered and two picture postcards from Western Australian soldiers, to friends and family at home. The postcards depict unity in the conflict, with such messsages as "United we stand", "The cross of the Allies", "True joy & peace abide with you" and "Remember". One picture postcard has the message "La France jusqu'au bout secourra l'opprim??" printed on it. At least three of the postcards were sent from France and they are addressed to various people in Doncaster Yorkshire, Portland Australia, and Cottesloe and Walliston, Western Australia. Most of the postcards relate to World War I and are dated 1917. Some are addressed to "Miss M. Greaves".

Creator: Dease Studios,
Title: First Anzac Day luncheon celebration held at Perth Town Hall and St. George's Hall, 25th April, 1916.
Notes: BA2676/1 framed with invitation, menus and flyers for the luncheon.;The Soldiers' Welcoming Committee of Western Australia was formed in September 1915 with the object of comforting returning soldiers, enterataing and generally working for the benefit of members of the Expeditionary Forces.  The majority of members were women and the Committee was chaired by Edith Cowan. On the 25th April 1916, the soldiers marched from the corner of James and Barrack Streets through the city to The Esplanade where they were inspected by His Excellency the Governor. After the march the Soldiers' Welcoming Committee held a luncheon in the Perth Town Hall for those who had participated in the landing at Gallipoli. The response to the luncheon was so positive that plans were changed just days vefore the occasion to welcome home  all World War 1 soldiers and the lunch was held across two sites, at the Perth Town Hall and St Georges Hall. The men in the Town Hall were representative of the battalions which went ashore on the first day at Gallipoli. (An article describing the event is published in Kalgoorlie Miner 26 April 1916, p.4);There are two different photographs of these functions published in the Western Mail 28 April 1916, p.25.
Subject: Geographical: Perth Town Hall (Perth, W.A.);St George's Hall (Perth, W.A.)

Creator: Blackboy Hill Studio,
Title: W2 Reinf on parade 4/7/18, Blackboy Hill.
Notes: Caption title.;Alternate title interpreted by cataloguer.
Summary: Newspaper articles about this parade and these soldiers refer to them as '2nd Reinforcements "W'" (Daily News 4 July 1918, p.6, Sunday Times 21 July 1918, p.1 and Daily News 11 September 1918, p.5). The Reinforcements "W" (Western Australia) were raised starting in May 1918 and were reinforcements to any unit which required them on their arrival in France. Previously each battalion had raised its own reinforcements. (see a small explanatory item in the West Australian 4 May 1918, p.7)

Title: J. de Castilla 7.1.03.
Notes: Title is autograph on photograph.
Summary: Lieutenant John de Castilla D.S.O., veteran on the Boer War as an officer in the 2nd Western Australian Mounted Infantry contingent. He was of Scottish ancestry (Western Mail 27 January 1900, p.21) and had previously been elected as a councillor in the inaugural council of the new municipality of Claremont (Western Mail 9 September 1898, p.31 with photograph). In 1903 he accepted a position as a Major in the Transvaal Constabulary (Western Mail 16 November 1901, p.28)
